{
  "doc_id": "7018",
  "text": "Blockade of insulin receptor signaling within the recorded MSN was sufficient to prevent insulin-induced increases in excitatory transmission ( Figure 1D ), suggesting a mechanism involving feedback from MSNs to presynaptic glutamatergic terminals. Indeed, our data support a previously unidentified mechanism whereby insulin produces disinhibition mediated by opioid receptor activation ( Figure 5A ). Specifically, addition of the GABA B antagonist phaclofen or the opioid receptor antagonist (-)-naloxone was sufficient to prevent insulin-induced in-creases in excitatory transmission ( Figure 5B, C) . The role of opioid receptors was further confirmed by the inability of (+)-naloxone (which does not have any action at opioid receptors [CITATION_1] to prevent insulininduced increases in glutamate release ( Figure 5F ). Although few functional studies have examined the regulation of NAc glutamate release by endogenous opioids, this mechanism is consistent with anatomical and physiological data. Specifically, Mu opioid receptors are located on presynaptic GABAergic terminals within the NAc [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and Mu opioid receptor activation reduces GABA release in the hippocampus and sub-thalamic nucleus [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . In addition, GABA B receptors are located on glutamatergic terminals within the striatum where they inhibit excitatory transmission [CITATION_9] . Thus, it is feasible for endogenous opioids to produce the disinhibition observed here, although future studies are needed to determine which specific type or types of opioid receptor are involved [CITATION_10] Banghart et al., 2015; [CITATION_11] .",
